Import, Wrangle, and Clean Dataset¶

In [107]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# import and use pandas to read and store the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("heart_2020_cleaned.csv")

Taking a look at the dataset, it contains both categorical and numeric data. Categorical data includes: HeartDisease, Smoking, AlcoholDrinking, Stroke, DiffWalking, Sex, AgeCategory, Race, Diabetic, PhysicalActivity, GenHealth, Asthma, KidneyDisease, and SkinCancer. Numeric data includes: BMI, PhysicalHealth, MentalHealth, and SleepTime. Later we will use LabelEncoder to transform the categorical data so it can be easily read by the machine learning models in Python.

Exploratory Analysis and Visualizations¶

The next step is plotting the data to identify and visualize any trends or issues in the data set. As seen by the plots below, there are far more "No" classes for HeartDisease, AlcoholDrinking, Stroke, DiffWalking, Diabetic, PhysicalActivity, Asthma, KidneyDisease, and SkinCancer. The most common race seen in the dataset is "White", the AgeCategory is somewhat similar but 60-64 & 65-69 are the most common, and most have "very good" GenHealth.

In [109]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# create a new dataframe with only the categorical variables from the original dataset
categorical_data = df.select_dtypes(include=[object])

# make a grid for the graphs to be placed in
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=7, ncols=2, figsize=(25,35))
axes = axes.flatten()

# for loop takes each column in the dataset, counts values, and plots a graph
for i, col in enumerate(categorical_data.columns):
    category_counts = df[col].value_counts()
    
    axes[i].bar(category_counts.index, category_counts.values)
    axes[i].set_title(col)
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Categories')
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Now looking at the numeric variables, BMI and SleepTime look to be pretty even in distribution when compared to "Yes" and "No" for HeartDisease. While PhysicalHealth and MentalHealth seem to have a wider distribution of "No" for HeartDisease.

More Data Wrangling¶

The function LabelEncoder is used to transform the categorical values so the Python can easily run machine learning models. For example, Smoking[Yes, No] transform into Smoking[1, 0] where "Yes" = 1 and "No" = 0.

In [112]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# go through the dataset and if a column is categorical, transform the variables using LabelEncoder
df["HeartDisease"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['HeartDisease']).transform(df['HeartDisease'])
df["Smoking"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Smoking']).transform(df['Smoking'])
df["AlcoholDrinking"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['AlcoholDrinking']).transform(df['AlcoholDrinking'])
df["Stroke"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Stroke']).transform(df['Stroke'])
df["DiffWalking"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['DiffWalking']).transform(df['DiffWalking'])
df["Sex"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Sex']).transform(df['Sex'])
df["AgeCategory"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['AgeCategory']).transform(df['AgeCategory'])
df["Race"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Race']).transform(df['Race'])
df["Diabetic"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Diabetic']).transform(df['Diabetic'])
df["PhysicalActivity"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['PhysicalActivity']).transform(df['PhysicalActivity'])
df["GenHealth"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['GenHealth']).transform(df['GenHealth'])
df["Asthma"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['Asthma']).transform(df['Asthma'])
df["KidneyDisease"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['KidneyDisease']).transform(df['KidneyDisease'])
df["SkinCancer"] = LabelEncoder().fit(df['SkinCancer']).transform(df['SkinCancer'])

Now split the clean and encoded dataset into Training and Testing sets. Splitting the dataset is important to estimate the performance of machine learning models and prevent overfitting or prevent the model on not performing well on unseen data. The most common split is 20% for testing and 80% for training the model.

In [113]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# create train and test set with 80% training and 20% testing
train_df, test_df = train_test_split(df, train_size=0.80) 

# split independent and dependent variables for training 
X_train= train_df.drop('HeartDisease', axis=1)
y_train= train_df['HeartDisease']

# split independent and dependent variables for testing 
X_test= test_df.drop('HeartDisease', axis=1)
y_test= test_df['HeartDisease']

Here, we have an issue of imbalance training data for the dependent variable. This can cause issues in model performance and interpretation. Imbalanced data can:

- lead to the accuracy score being better than what it really is, inaccurate performace results 
- be biased towards the majority class only
- lead to overfitting

To solve this issue, SMOTE is used. SMOTE is a oversampling technique. Here the sample size of the Minority class is increased to match it with the sample size of Majority Class. In this example, "Yes" or 1 is the Minority class and "No" or 0 is the Majority class.

After oversampling, the new training set called y_SMOTE and has the same numbers of Yes and No!

Last, we standardize and normalize all the independent values for better model performance.

X_train_smote , y_train_smote = smote.fit_resample(X_train,y_train)

Machine Learning Models¶

Can you indicate which variables have a significant effect on the likelihood of heart disease?

  • Based on the simple logistic regression below, all of the variables except Race are significant because they have a very low p-value.
  • It is important to note that the model is very simple and has a low adjusted R^2. More advanced models can be made, but you lose interpretability.

Compared to all the models tested (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, AdaBoost, and XGBoost), the Random Forest model performed the best. It had the highest accuracy, highest true negative, lowest false positve, but the highest false negative. But overall, it performs the best compared to the other models.

In [117]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

# using all values to see which variables are significant
X = df.drop(columns = ["HeartDisease"])
y = df['HeartDisease']

# fit the Logistic model
results = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

# print the stats 
print(results.summary())

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# fit on training and predict on testing dataset
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# get the accuracy score
score = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print('Accuracy = %.2f' % (score*100) + '%')

Accuracy = 70.32%

The Logistic Regression Model has a very high false postive
